      "turn_number": 1,
      "role": "interviewer",
      "type": "opening",
      "text": "Hello Cherelle, thank you so much for taking the time to speak with me today. I'm a researcher studying maternity care experiences, and I'm really interested in hearing your personal story. I understand you're in the early stages of pregnancy, and I'd love to hear about your experience in your own words. There are no right or wrong answers — I'm just here to listen and learn from you. Everything you share will help us understand how to make maternity care better. Shall we begin?",
      "question_id": null,
      "probe_id": null,
      "target_dimensions": [],
      "target_latent": [],
      "input_tokens": 0,
      "output_tokens": 0
    },
    {
      "turn_number": 2,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "Yes, thank you for asking — I’m glad someone wants to listen. I’m nineteen, in my first trimester, and half the time I feel like I’m holding my breath. At appointments I try to sound calm and use the right words — “nausea,” “spotting,” “mild cramping” — because I’m scared they’ll write me off if I seem hysterical. My doctor says I’m low risk, and on paper I look fine, but she doesn’t see my hands shaking when I leave or the way my chest tightens thinking about being a single parent.\n\nLast week I saw the ultrasound and that little heartbeat flickered on the screen. For a second everything quieted and I cried in the car — I didn’t expect to feel relief that strong. I have a history of depression, and the fear that it’ll come back and steal this from me is constant. I want to be the kind of parent who understands her body and asks questions, not just nods. Right now I’m juggling job hunting, appointments, and a silence at home that’s hard to fill. I just want to be heard, not treated like a checklist.",
      "responding_to_question_id": null,
      "input_tokens": 730,
      "output_tokens": 439
    },
